manufacturerProductDescription.media_text: Feel the Rush of Ripjaws V Ripjaws V series DDR4 DRAM memory is designed for sleek aesthetics and performance, making it an ideal choice for building a new PC system or for upgrading your system memory.

Experience DDR4 Performance Available in a wide range of frequency options, Ripjaws V series lets you enjoy a computing experience at DDR4 speeds for gaming, video & image editing, rendering, and data processing.
Outstanding Quality The Ripjaws V DDR4 memory series undergoes G.SKILL's rigorous production process to ensure outstanding quality.

XMP 2.0 Support Just set and go. Programmed with the latest Intel XMP 2.0 profiles, the only thing between you and overclocked performance is a simple BIOS setting. (*Enable the XMP profile in the BIOS to reach up to the rated overclock speed of this memory kit. Maximum memory speed and system stability depends on the capability of the motherboard & CPU. The memory kit will boot at the SPD speed when BIOS settings are at default.)

42mm Module Height Designed with a 42mm module height, the Ripjaws V series memory is ideal for use with large CPU coolers. (*Please check the specifications of your CPU cooler for actual height clearance.)

reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars 2 sticks run XMP at 3200MHz on Z170A board with I7-7700k @4.5GHz
reviews.reviewText: As the headline says, very happy with the performance results on my very pick I7-7700k. Have had issues getting it to run the XMP profile @ 3200 MHz. Had 2 sticks of 8GB G.Skill memory and could never get XMP to work, and only able to run at 3000 MHz. Installed these 2 sticks of 16GB, and XMP worked right out of the box. No tinkering required. Very happy and breathed some new life into my aging desktop. Can now run Ubuntu with Virtualbox and Windows 10 client with lots of RAM. Very satisfied.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on July 20, 2022
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars PC Tech of 35 yrs - keep buying these for older boards to save money in the future
reviews.reviewText: Every 3 years, the price of RAM fluctuates from high to low and back again, as all the wafer FAB plants need to retool for never versions of RAM.This month, (July 2022) we are now at all time super LOW price.I have been buying GSKILL ram since 2009. In 2009, I was like 'G-who?' and gave them a try.Today, after assembling hundreds of systems, I believe GSKILLs as good as if not better than Corsair... and wayyyyyyyyyyyyyy better than the overrated Micron OEM and Kingston whole products. Yes, I try other brands occasionally and have done fine with Patriot as well.. but for overall best in class, GSkill is my choice.Lately, been replacing RAM on older 8th, 9th 10th and 11th gen systems (usually DDR4 2300 - DDR 2800) with these GSKill 32 GB 3200 module kits. The reason is simple. I believe RAM has hit an all time low in price and will only go up again.Fear not about the swap out. This RAM slows down in older boards to match the bios settings. And that means if the board fails in a few years, you now have THIS RAM ready for the board replacement.Newbie advice: enter the board bios and set up XMP boost for your RAM, as some boards default to 2133 Ghz. Many board no longer match the RAM speed to the CPU unless the XMP feature is enabled and you press 'save all settings' upon exit.If you were thinking of mixing and matching other brands.. even in different channel slots.. JUST FORGET IT. Super bad idea... as it may boot, but later on, cause system crashes. Instead buy the GKSILL 32 GB set and leave any other open slots alone. Later down the road, you can buy two more identical modules, providing your board has 4 RAM slots.The latest 12th system builds I have been building for myself and clients.. have the bios XMP ready for DDR4 3200 speed RAM. My favorite pairings include the i3-12100 (read the reviews on this CPU, it's powerful) and 4th gen Samsung 980 PRO SSD. My main choice for boards is MSI and if you want to drive many monitors and you are not a gamer, look for the MSI board with FOUR video outputs on the rear that run off the CPU video.
